Colombian Peso Rises to Two-Week High on Increased Demand

-- B y   A n d r e a   J a r a m i l l o
-- 
2011-06-30T14:54:53Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-30/colombian-peso-rises-to-two-week-high-on-increased-demand.html
Colombia ’s peso rose to a two-week
high as optimism  Greece  will avoid a default boosted demand for
higher-yielding, emerging-market assets.  The peso climbed 0.3 percent to 1,774.60 per dollar at
10:18 a.m. New York time, from 1,779.50 yesterday. That’s its
strongest level on an intraday basis since June 14. The peso has
jumped 5.5 percent so far this quarter, the best performer in
emerging markets.  Greek Prime Minister  George Papandreou  gained approval
today from lawmakers to implement his 78 billion-euro ($113
billion) package of budget cuts and asset sales after winning
parliamentary backing yesterday for the bill.  “External markets are a bit calmer now that things in
Greece are happening as the market has been expecting,” said
Juan Camilo Santana, an analyst at Bogota-based brokerage Cia.
de Profesionales de Bolsa SA. “ Risk aversion  is down, helping
emerging-market currencies, including the Colombian peso and the
Brazilian real.”  The yield on Colombia’s 10 percent bonds due July 2024 fell
one basis point, or 0.01 percentage point, to 7.76 percent,
according to Colombia’s stock exchange. The security’s price
rose 0.065 centavo to 118.015 centavo per peso.  To contact the reporter on this story:
